      <h4>Speaking to God as Father</h4>
      <p>Latter-day Saints are taught to pray morning and evening, individually and as families. We kneel when possible. We address our Heavenly Father directly — not through saints, angels, or intermediaries — and close in the name of Jesus Christ. Prayer is not recitation. It is conversation: thanksgiving, confession, petition, and listening.</p>
      <p>The Prophet Alma taught his people to "cry unto God for all their support" and to "let their hearts be full, drawn out in prayer unto him continually" (<a class="scripture-link" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/bofm/alma/34?id=p27#p27" target="_blank">Alma 34:27</a>). This is not performance. It is relationship — the most important relationship any soul can cultivate.</p>

    blesses: |
      <h4>A Witness of Daily Prayer</h4>
      <p>There was a season when I prayed out of duty and nothing else. I said the words, but my heart was a closed fist. Then one morning, after a night of deep trouble, I had nothing eloquent to offer — only "Father, I need Thee." That was all. And something broke open. Not the heavens. Something in me.</p>
      <p>Daily prayer has not made my life easy. But it has made me known to God in a way I cannot explain to anyone who has not experienced it. I have felt His awareness of me — not as a case to manage, but as a son He is shaping. The constancy of showing up before Him, even imperfectly, has changed the architecture of my soul.</p>
      <p class="bridge-text">If this resonates with you — or even if you are not sure it does — the next step invites you to choose one practice that fits where you are right now.</p>

