    practice: |
      <h4>Daily Course Correction, Not Crisis Management</h4>
      <p>Many traditions treat repentance as an emergency measure — the response to serious transgression. Latter-day Saints believe that too, but we also understand repentance as a daily practice. It is the ongoing work of aligning our will with God's will. President Russell M. Nelson has taught that repentance is among the most joyful of all gospel principles — not because sin is trivial, but because the Savior's Atonement makes real change possible every single day.</p>
      <p>Repentance in its fullest Latter-day Saint sense involves recognition, godly sorrow, confession to God (and to priesthood leaders when necessary), abandonment of the sin, and restitution where possible. But the daily practice is simpler: honest self-examination, humble acknowledgment before God, and a sincere turning of the heart. The sacrament (communion) each Sunday provides a covenant renewal — a weekly reset in which we recommit and receive the promise of His Spirit again.</p>

    blesses: |
      <h4>The Freedom of Turning</h4>
      <p>I carried a grudge for years that I had convinced myself was righteous indignation. It poisoned conversations I didn't even know it was touching. When the Spirit finally showed me what I was doing — not in condemnation, but with piercing clarity — I did not feel crushed. I felt relieved. The weight had a name now, and it could be set down.</p>
      <p>That is what daily repentance has become in my life: not a catalogue of failures, but a willingness to be shown what I cannot see. The Savior does not expose our weakness to humiliate us. He exposes it so we can hand it to Him. "Come unto me," He said, "all ye that labour and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest" (<a class="scripture-link" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/nt/matt/11?id=p28#p28" target="_blank">Matthew 11:28</a>). That rest is real. I have felt it.</p>
      <p class="bridge-text">What might God be inviting you to set down? The commitment below offers a way to begin.</p>

