    practice: |
      <h4>Willful Hunger with Sacred Purpose</h4>
      <p>On the first Sunday of each month, Latter-day Saints fast for two consecutive meals and donate the money saved — or more — as a "fast offering" to care for the poor. This is not a diet strategy or a spiritual stunt. It is an act of deliberate dependence on God, a physical declaration that "man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceedeth out of the mouth of God" (<a class="scripture-link" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/nt/matt/4?id=p4#p4" target="_blank">Matthew 4:4</a>).</p>
      <p>Beyond the monthly fast, Saints fast whenever they face decisions that require divine guidance, when they seek healing for themselves or others, or when they need added spiritual power to overcome temptation. Alma testified that he had "fasted and prayed many days that I might know these things of myself" (<a class="scripture-link" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/bofm/alma/5?id=p46#p46" target="_blank">Alma 5:46</a>). Fasting sharpens spiritual receptivity in a way that prayer alone sometimes does not.</p>

    blesses: |
      <h4>What Hunger Taught Me</h4>
      <p>The first few fasts I kept were miserable. I watched the clock, thought about food, and accomplished nothing spiritual. I was fasting from meals. I had not yet learned to fast toward God.</p>
      <p>The fast that changed me came when my brother was diagnosed with cancer. I could not fix it. I could not pray eloquently. But I could give God my appetite, my comfort, my self-sufficiency — and say, "I have nothing left to offer but my willingness to go without." That fast was the most connected I have ever felt to the Savior, who went forty days without food and then faced the adversary with nothing but the word of God.</p>
      <p>Fasting does not manipulate God. It changes us. It strips away the noise and leaves us open to hear Him in ways our comfortable lives often do not permit.</p>
      <p class="bridge-text">Whether fasting is familiar to you or entirely new, choose a practice below that stretches you without breaking you.</p>

    commitments:
