      <h4>Examining the State of Your Soul</h4>
      <p>Latter-day Saints practice regular spiritual self-assessment through multiple channels. Before participating in sacred temple ordinances, members meet privately with their bishop and answer questions about their faithfulness, honesty, family relationships, and obedience to covenants. This is not an inquisition — it is an invitation to honest reflection with a spiritual shepherd.</p>
      <p>But temple recommend interviews are not the only form of self-assessment. The Apostle Paul instructed the Corinthians to "examine yourselves, whether ye be in the faith" (<a class="scripture-link" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/nt/2-cor/13?id=p5#p5" target="_blank">2 Corinthians 13:5</a>). Alma asked his people, "Have ye spiritually been born of God? Have ye received his image in your countenances? Have ye experienced this mighty change in your hearts?" (<a class="scripture-link" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/bofm/alma/5?id=p14#p14" target="_blank">Alma 5:14</a>). These questions are not meant to produce guilt. They are meant to produce clarity.</p>
      <p>Whether you participate in formal worthiness interviews or not, the practice of honest spiritual inventory — asking yourself hard questions before God — is a discipline available to every person.</p>

    blesses: |
      <h4>The Gift of Being Seen</h4>
      <p>I once dreaded these conversations. I walked into the bishop's office carrying my inadequacies like a grocery list, certain that I would be found wanting. What I discovered was something different: a man called of God who listened with compassion, pointed me toward the Savior, and helped me see that the point was never perfection — it was direction.</p>
      <p>Self-assessment, when practiced in the Spirit, is not about scorekeeping. It is about trajectory. Am I moving toward Christ or away from Him? Am I kinder than I was six months ago? Do I pray with more intent? Have I kept my promises? These are the questions that matter, and they lose their sting when asked in the presence of grace.</p>
      <p class="bridge-text">The commitment below invites you to examine where you stand — not to condemn yourself, but to choose where you are heading.</p>

